Well, I hung the other birdhouse during the day. Here's what it looks like in a good spot in the garden.
But, little flashback: "What's inside?", I don't hear someone asking.
At the top is one of these ESP32 modules with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED that I recovered from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box has a strange shape, it's because of the pivoting side panel of the feeder. I bought it like that and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my setup around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the entire system is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 battery cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a photo of the panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the feeder houses the battery.
At full charge, it gives me about 4 hours of power.
I call this a feature. That way, the birds can also have a bit of privacy.
At first, I didn't know if the Internet connection in our garden would be strong enough for this installation. The old access points I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been sufficient.
But the new ones cover the area well.
It's almost disappointing because I had planned to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof and point it downward toward the garden.
I could always do it when I install more camera nest boxes, especially in areas far from the house, I might need them.
